          "content": "Yes, this is tracking! You want to create a new file that handles Python code modifications using a pytest-style scope syntax for precise targeting. Let me break down my understanding:\n\n1. Scope Syntax:\n   - `filename.py::ClassName::MethodName`\n   - `filename.py::ClassName::SubClassName::MethodName`\n   - Can target files, classes, methods at any nesting level\n\n2. Default Behavior:\n   - Replace the targeted node\n\n3. Optional Insert Behavior via two methods:\n   a. Line-based:\n   - Specify an `insert_after` line\n   - If exactly one whitespace-normalized match is found\n   - New node inserted after that line with same scope\n   \n   b. Scope-based:\n   - `insert_after` can be a scope like `ClassName::MethodName`\n   - Helps disambiguate when adding to end of specific scopes\n   - Maintains proper nesting level\n\nQuestions for clarification:\n1. Should we maintain the same function names (add_function, replace_function, etc.) or create a new unified interface?\n2. For the line-based insert_after, should we support regex or just exact matching?\n3. Should we support inserting before as well as after?\n4. Do we need to maintain all the current functionality (like handling imports) or can we simplify?\n\nWould you like me to proceed with creating the new file once you address these questions?",
